The constitutional amendment that would raise the age limit for the office of president, allowing the then seventy-three-year-old Yoweri Museveni to re-enter, was not appreciated by all MPs, one of whom launched a chair against the presidential flag to be immediately drafted by a colleague. In the parapilla that followed some politicians faced with metal bars>.&nbsp;
<h2>Taiwan, 13 July 2017</h2>
The infrastructure projects promoted by President Tsai Ing-wen in 2017 were so controversial that the parliamentarian Chu Yi-ying, elected with the majority, and Hsu shu-hua, of the opposition party Kuomintang, tried to strangle each other. In the barrage that followed, the colleagues managed to separate them. The House of Taipei is often the scene of similar episodes. Four years earlier, some Members had even moved on to a disside on how to tax capital gains.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2>Sudafrica, 9 February 2017</h2>
The speech at the Nation of the then South African President Jacob Zuma, was interrupted by the boats of the radical left of the Economic Freedom Fighters. The situation soon degenerated and the orders were forced to use force to drag out the MPs of the formation of Julius Malema. The president of the House, Mbaleka Mbete would have apologized for giving Malema the "scarafage", that is the same epithet that the Huthu used against the Tutsi, exterminated during the genocide that sansguinated Rwanda in 1994.
<h2>Turkey, 20 January 2017</h2>
Turkey shares with Ukraine and Taiwan the podium of the countries with the most reluctant parliaments. It's really hard to choose a case on everyone. We therefore mention the session of 20 January 2017, the first in the history of the Great National Assembly to see a physical confrontation between women. The object of the dispute is the constitutional reform which would consolidate the power of the President. Some Akp MPs, Erdogan's party, were involved in a clash with republican exponents of the Chp who soon became a colluct. Between punches, slaps and pulled hair, the budget was four wounds.
<h2>Nepal, 20 January 2015</h2>
The new Constitution presented in 2015 was not appreciated by Maoist politicians, heirs of the rebels who unleashed the civil war in 2006, who stood on their benches and began to draw shoes and microphones against the majority. Three commissions, intervened to sedate the souls ended in hospital.&nbsp;
