AGI - "Israel will carry out a counter-retaliation on Iran to restore balance: for decades the rule of deterrence says that it must beat with force and last and rarely has derogated." Riccardo Alcaro, head of the Global Attori program of the International Business Institute (Iai), interviewed by AGI in light of the launch of hundreds of drones and missiles by the Islamic Republic on Saturday night against the Jewish State. A retaliation after the April 1 raid against the Iranian consulate in Damascus where several Pasdaran were killed, including General Mohammad Reza Zahedi.
&nbsp;
The Iranian attack, threatened and announced in advance, was of strong symbolic impact but did limited damage. It remains to see how Israel will react: The war cabinet met several times but so far no decision has been taken. For Alcaro, "the Israeli government has strong internal incentives not to let Iran have the last word. First of all, military: one of the pillars of the doctrine of deterrence applied in recent decades says that Israel must strike with force and last, a principle which has rarely derogated, not in the last 30 years."&nbsp; besides, adds the analyst, there are reasons related to the "internal balances to the Israeli executive, erected by a right-wing and ultra-right coalition. The desire to respond to Iran is widespread and general and can be even existential to the government if the two extremist parties of Itamar Ben-Gvir and Bezalel Smotrich put the condition that without Israeli retaliation they would withdraw support."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Finally, Alcaro says, there are "the personal reasons of Premier Benjamin Netanyahu, who knows very well that in case of elections, he would lose. And at that point he would be presented the account, for the disaster of October 7 and for the apparent failure of the strategy followed, since the war in Gaza has not reached any of the objectives indicated, neither the return of the hostages nor the destruction of Hamas". Not to mention, his "problems for a long time with justice". "To avoid the elections, the best option for Netanyahu is that the war continues and that the focus moves from Gaza - on which Israel is necessarily on the defensive, given the level of devastation totally disproportionate to what it has suffered on October 7 - to Iran, on which it has played quite easy in gathering the support of the U.S. and the main European countries".
&nbsp;
"I don't see any disincentives doing a counter-retaliation," says Alcaro. "There are political risks - to create a fracture with Americans - and military risks. The U.S. has announced that they will not participate in an offensive, so Israel must well set the type of response. Netanyahu is used to pull the rope, and it may be that his calculation" leads him to risk, thinking that "even if the U.S. has said that they will not intervene in a counter-retaliation, if this should trigger a further escalation and arrive at an open conflict with Iran, they would still intervene in favor of Israel.
&nbsp;
And so it could be that the government decides for a high-level political retaliation, that is, really hitting hard." As for the possible objectives, "Israel has many options", he recalls the analyst of the Iai, convinced that in question there is "an attack from the Israeli territory to the Iranian territory to restore equality >". But the rest is hard to predict. The idea remains that "there is in the Israeli security and military establishment, who says that this counter-retaliation should be made so that it is acceptable to partners, firstly the U.S., Europeans and Arab countries, so that it cannot be automatically considered as an escalation".
