AGI - "I'm quite convinced that there will be a reaction from Israel, but I don't think it's going to open a new face of conflict. I think there will be a reaction, but I hope it will be contained, more tactical." is the hope of the Minister of Defense, Guido&nbsp;Crosetto, interviewed on SkyTg24.&nbsp;
Per&nbsp;Crosetto&nbsp; "we are to those we could still call 'scaramucce', although the Iranian attack, the first in the history of the complicated relationship between Israel and Iran of such a magnitude, was an attack that in any other nation in the world would have a disastrous effect." The Defence Minister observed that what Tehran accomplished "had no effect because it happened on a nation that probably has the best air defense system that exists, proportional to the territory." "But the amount of drones, ballistic missiles, cruise missiles that were shipped to Israel would cause huge damage to any other nation. There weren't any in Israel because they managed to break down 99% of these attacks, but it was a very hard attack.&nbsp; I think that Iran's attack could not have any consequences from the international point of view - he added the Minister of Defense -. It will be a decision of the international community." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
The appeals to Israel from the international community to "do not open an even larger war front" exposing itself to the reprisal of Iran are based on "a reasoning of common sense also made in the interest of Israel. Washington was very precise - Crosetto explained -: while the speaker of the House announced a package of economic aid that was very relevant to Israel, he said that the United States will never enter into a war or an attack on Iran". The minister recalled the "meaning support given by the United States, Great Britain, France, Jordan" to thwart the attack with drones and missiles against Israel. "There has been a contest of countries in aid of Israel and this will continue on the part of the United States, but they will not support any offensive against Iran. That was clear. As the international community has been clear with Israel saying 'we avoid opening another conflict, opening an even greater war front'. But this seems to me a reasoning of common sense even in the interest of Israel."
&nbsp;
Crosetto then observed how never in the Middle East can not start paths of peace: "And because of the UN's inability to look at the facts objectively. The split that exists in the UN also deprived the world of an entity capable of affirming what is the right thing to do and what is international law. It is necessary to rebuild the credibility and strength of the UN that is now blocked for the vetoes of Russia, China, USA according to the conflicts and the partiality with which each State faces any conflict is paralyzing the world and bringing it to the brink of a precipice."

